{"id":"project-LICHEN-796f","title":"announce.c: EUI-64 to IID conversion may conflict with pubkey-derived IID","description":"File: lichen/subsys/lichen/routing/announce.c
Lines: 517-519 vs lines 67-84

In build_announce_frame() (scheduler TX path), IID is derived from EUI-64:

    memcpy(iid, sched.link_ctx->eui64, LICHEN_ANNOUNCE_IID_LEN);
    iid[0] ^= 0x02U; /* EUI-64 to IID conversion */

But in pubkey_to_iid() (RX verification path):

    (void)tc_sha256_final(hash, &sha_state);
    memcpy(iid, hash, LICHEN_ANNOUNCE_IID_LEN);
    iid[0] &= (uint8_t)~0x02U;

The TX path uses EUI-64 with bit 6 flipped, while RX expects IID = SHA256(pubkey)[0:8] with bit 1 cleared.

Unless EUI-64 happens to equal SHA256(pubkey)[0:8] (extremely unlikely), the signature verification will ALWAYS fail because the signed IID won't match the expected pubkey-derived IID.

This appears to be a protocol implementation bug - either TX should use pubkey_to_iid(), or the verification logic needs to accept EUI-64-derived IIDs.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"me@mark.atwood.name","created_at":"2026-07-12T06:50:42.220694Z","created_by":"Mark Atwood","updated_at":"2026-07-12T06:50:42.22073Z"}

